predict.regsubsets=function(object,newdata,id,...){ form=as.formula(object$call[[2]]) 
mat=model.matrix(form,newdata) 
coefi=coef(object,id=id)
xvars=names(coefi)
mat[,xvars]%*%coefi
}

Problem 3: Properties of k-fold cross validation Suppose we are given a training set with n observations and want to conduct k-fold cross-validation. Assume always that n = km where m is an integer.

a: Let k = 2. Explain carefully why there are 1􏰙n􏰚 ways to partition the data into 2 folds. 2m # k=2 means that we need to divide n observations into 2 parts. So we can calculate the number of ways selecting n samples out of n observations. Since each sample group has been calculated twice (being selected and being left), we need to divide the number of ways by 2.

(1/2)(n!/(m! m!))

b: Let k = 3. Explain carefully why there are n! ways to partition the data into 3 folds. 3!m!m!m! # k=3 means that we need to select m samples out of n observations. Then we select m samples from the left (n-m) samples. Each sample group has been calculated 3! times, so we need to divide the number of ways by 3!.

(1/3!) * (n!/(m! * m! * m!))

c: Guess a formula for the number of ways to partition the data into k folds for general k. Check if your formula gives the correct answer for k=n (leave-one-out c.v.). # (1/k!) * (n!/(m!)^k)
